## Features
- single shell script
- example website and assets provided
- all under CC0 - public domain
- fast and simple to setup and configure
- minimal dependencies: just the `pandoc` on unix-like systems
- generates static content: easy to host anywhere
- syntax highlighting out of the box
- blog and photogallery out of the box

## Install
Built and tested on Debian 10. To get the demo page up:
- Install pandoc (>v2.0), make sure you have shell and common UNIX utilities
- Download or clone this repository: `git clone https://github.com/frainfreeze/tundra.git`
- Make script executable: `chmod a+rx ./tundra.sh` or run it using `sh thundra.sh`
- Run the script and open newly created `index.html` in your web browser.

> NOTE: If you want to use this script on *BSD or macOS, please make sure you have the GNU implementation of `awk` and `sed` installed.

To customize the site simple edit included files and add new content. You are free to edit the tundra.sh file as well, but if you
want to keep simple update path I advise you to use pre/post/clean scripts functionality instead.


## Configure
There are two types of configuration: per project (your site) and per page.

To extend tundra.sh you can use the pre/post scripts or edit tundra.sh directly.

### Site configuration
On top of `tundra.sh` are hardcoded default configuration variables. These get overriden by the `site_conf.sh` if it exists
in the same folder as `tundra.sh`.

You can use them to change page theme, markdown flavor etc.

The values are following:

| Variable    | Description |
| ----------- | ----------- |
| AUTHOR      | Site author |
| BLOG_TITLE  | Blog subtitle |
| ROOT | Site working directory, defaults to directory tundra.sh is in |
| SITE_RES | Global site resources (scripts, styles), defaults to ROOT/res |
| INDEX_PATH | Location of site index file, defaults to README.md |
| INDEX_RES | Location of site's index file resource folder, defaults to SITE_RES |
| POSTS_PATH  | Location of sites blog posts, defaults to ROOT/posts |
| POSTS_RES | Location of site's blog posts resource folder, defaults to SITE_RES |
| PAGES_PATH | Location of sites sub-pages, defaults to ROOT/pages |
| PAGES_RES | Location of site's subpages resource folder, defaults to SITE_RES |
| MD_FLAVOUR | Site's markdown flavour. defauts to markdown_github+yaml_metadata_block |

Custom *_RES(ources) folders are provided so you can set custom styling, scripts and 
other resources for different parts of your site.


### Per page configuration

`pandoc` supports YAML blocks, this is self-explanatory example:

```yaml
---
title: "Example title"
author: "author"
date: 2023-01-21
---
```

I recommend you to keep the block on the top of the file. 
See [pandoc documentation](https://pandoc.org/MANUAL.html#extension-yaml_metadata_block) for more details.

## Customize & extend
To change index page simply edit this readme or configure tundra to point at your own index file - see the site configuration above.
You can also use the `--index` option to give a file to be used (defaults to `README.md`).

To make new blog posts add source files to posts folder.

Tundra also searches for pre/post/clean scripts. They should be placed in res folder

Run `./tundra.sh -h` to see available options.
